Pwani University and Kenya Medical Research Institute have launched a state of the art bioscience research centre at the varsity. The Sh100 million Pwani University Bioscience Research Centre was launched on Tuesday. Kemri-Wellcome Trust and Pwani University funded the project. The university gave Sh50 million for construction and Kemri equipped the lab with more than Sh50 million. The centre is expected to be one of the best research facility at the Coast. The construction of the molecular lab started in 2016. Pwani University vice chancellor Prof Mohamed Rajab said the centre will research on malaria and other diseases, which Kemri has been undertaking at its institute in Kilifi.  “The lab is supporting 12 researchers’ work. It will also enhance the malaria research programme, which Kemri has been doing for several years,” said Rajab.  